This response actually depends on the film itself. If I am eager (which means I know something about the film), then I will try to catch as much snippets, previews or any content I can in anticipation. It's not so much curiosity but my eagerness to consume the product already. Truth be told, I haven't had that feeling for many films of late. They are more of passing events. As such, I don't seek out trailers as a routine either.

Again, I prefer spoilers, especially of competition shows where there are leaks with renown accuracy (e.g. MTV's The Challenge where at vevmo , a regular who is consistently on the money posts the entire list of the elimination results. And I like living on the West coast where any delayed shows (with the award ceremonies hosted on the East coast) I can go online and find the list of winners before they are revealed on the televised broadcast aired on the west coast.

I answered I sometimes seek out spoilers because I do both. I actively seek spoilers for some things, but avoid them for others. I actively avoid spoilers for TV shows, Books, Movies, etc because these are driven mainly by story/narrative elements that I want to experience as a full picture (not isolated as spoilers are). This means I can develop emotions and my own perspective in the way intended by the creator/artist. However I sometimes seek spoilers for video games, specifically live service ones. Sometimes upcoming characters and their abilities are released prior to their intended release, and this gives me a better idea whether I want to invest my time or not. However, I still actively avoid story spoilers whenever possible for these games.

Sometimes watching the trailer can give me a better idea whether to see the movie in theatres or wait until it is cheaper. I only avoid trailers if I have been waiting for the specific movie(e.g., Dune, where I had read the books years prior)
